The paper deals with randomized algorithms and their randomness complexity, which are topics typically studied in the computational complexity (cs.CC) and information theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. The use of pseudorandom generators and the analysis of error and failure probabilities suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. Finally, the application of the results to a specific problem in computational learning theory suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
